                        </button>
                    </div>

                </div>
            </aside>


            <!-- ===== RIGHT: Main Article Content ===== -->
            <main class="col-span-12 lg:col-span-9">

                <!-- TL;DR -->
                <section class="mb-14" id="tldr">
                    <TldrCard items={[
                        { label: "Core Thesis", text: "Autodesk's subscription pivot required a fundamental shift from product-push to account-centric engagement. ABM became the operating system for that shift." },
                        { label: "Key Insight", text: "Naming it \"ABSM\" (Account-Based Sales and Marketing) was a deliberate move. Joint KPIs with sales and 1:1 \"account therapy\" sessions made alignment real, not aspirational." },
                        { label: "Practitioner Takeaway", text: "Personalized microsites via Folloze scaled ABM to 10,000 global accounts within a year. Digital + physical direct mail made it memorable." },
                        { label: "Contrarian View", text: "Revenue grew from $2.1B to $5.3B (FY18-FY24), but isolating ABM's contribution from the broader subscription shift remains impossible to prove." }
                    ]} />
                </section>


                <!-- ===== SECTION 01: A New Era ===== -->
                <section class="mb-14" id="new-era">
                    <SectionHeader number="01" title="A New Era Under Anagnost" />

                    <article class="article-prose space-y-6">
                        <p>
                            In 2018, Autodesk, the San Francisco stalwart known for its design, engineering, and entertainment software, faced a choice. The company, transitioning from a traditional sales model to a subscription-based business, needed a new strategy to effectively engage and retain high-value customers.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            In 2017, Autodesk elevated acting interim co-CEO and CMO <strong>Andrew Anagnost</strong> to the new role of President and CEO to drive the next phase of growth. With over 25 years at the company, Anagnost championed three strategic initiatives:
                        </p>

                        <ol>
                            <li>Completing transition to a subscription business model</li>
                            <li>Digitizing the company</li>
                            <li>Reimagining construction, manufacturing, and production</li>
                        </ol>

                        <!-- Inline Quote -->
                        <SpeakerQuote
                            quote="Our long tail of customers, our small customers, need different things than our biggest customers. How do you balance delighting current customers while providing next-gen, disruptive cloud-native solutions?"
                            speakerName="Andrew Anagnost"
                            speakerTitle="CEO, Autodesk"
                            initials="AA"
                            color="blue"
                        />

                        <p>
                            This balancing act between customer delight and disruption becomes even more significant when you realize that Autodesk had 12+ million legacy users and only 4 million of them were paying customers.
                        </p>
                    </article>
                </section>


                <!-- ===== SECTION 02: The ABM Imperative ===== -->
                <section class="mb-14" id="abm-imperative">
                    <SectionHeader number="02" title="The ABM Imperative" />

                    <article class="article-prose space-y-6">
                        <p>
                            While there were many levers to lead the transformation, an internal motion was set up to focus on account-based marketing. Why? The subscription shift demanded it:
                        </p>

                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>For the Customer, Of the Customer:</strong> Success now depended on how end-users actually used the product, necessitating long-term relationships.</li>
                            <li><strong>Cushion with Education:</strong> The subscription shift required tailored redress of customer anxieties through personalised education.</li>
                            <li><strong>Great Expectations:</strong> Annual subscriptions created heightened expectations for frequent upgrades and support.</li>
                            <li><strong>Plug the Leak:</strong> With continuous churn risk, focusing on the 80-20 rule became essential. 20% of customers drove 80% of revenue.</li>
                        </ul>

                        <AcmeTake>
                            The subscription model is what forces the ABM motion, not the other way around. If your revenue model shifts from one-time to recurring, your marketing model <em>must</em> shift from lead-centric to account-centric. This isn't optional.
                        </AcmeTake>
                    </article>
                </section>


                <!-- ===== SECTION 03: Aligning with Sales ===== -->
                <section class="mb-14" id="sales-alignment">
                    <SectionHeader number="03" title="Aligning with Sales" />

                    <article class="article-prose space-y-6">

                        <!-- Sub-section -->
                        <h3 class="text-xl brand-font uppercase text-[#006AB4]">AB'S'M: Another Bull-Shit Marketing?</h3>

                        <p>
                            Care was taken to portray unified execution even in naming: ABM was not just ABM, but AB'S'M &mdash; Account-Based Sales and Marketing. Sales and marketing were no longer operating in silos.
                        </p>

                        <SpeakerQuote
                            quote="This is ABSM, and we are now in the same boat, winning together."
                            speakerName="Christian Weiss"
                            speakerTitle="Director of ABM CE, Autodesk"
                            initials="CW"
                            color="red"
                        />

                        <p>
                            The response from the European mid-market sales team was skeptical. The sales leader bluntly asked: "ABSM? What does that mean? Another Bull-Shit in Marketing?" This skepticism highlighted the need for joint efforts and shared accountability.
                        </p>

                        <!-- Sub-section -->
                        <h3 class="text-xl brand-font uppercase text-[#E31C25]">Skin-in-the-Game: Joint KPIs</h3>

                        <p>
                            To build trust, the ABSM team carried a number on them, just like their sales counterparts. Shared KPIs included:
                        </p>

                        <!-- Data Table -->
                        <DataTable
                            headers={["KPI Category", "Metrics"]}
                            rows={[
                                ["Revenue", "Annual Contract Value, Subscriber goals (cloud + product licenses)"],
                                ["Account Health", "% Account Lift, Seat Expansion, Content Interactions, # of Demos"],
                                ["Deal Velocity", "Avg. deal size, % product mix, # net new contacts, # net new opportunities"],
                                ["Retention", "# of conversions, # of renewals, advocacy score"]
                            ]}
                        />

                        <!-- Sub-section -->
                        <h3 class="text-xl brand-font uppercase text-black">Account Therapy</h3>

                        <p>
                            The ABM team set up regular "1:1 account therapy" sessions with sales reps &mdash; designed to drive tight alignment and collaboration.
                        </p>

                        <SpeakerQuote
                            quote="We call it account therapy because sales already has a pipeline review. You don't want to intimidate them. Instead, it's 'come and vent to me as your marketer what your challenges are and I'll come up with ideas for you.'"
                            speakerName="Nathalie N. Moore"
                            speakerTitle="AEC ABM Manager, Autodesk"
                            initials="NM"
                            color="yellow"
                        />

                        <AcmeTake>
                            "Account therapy" is genius framing. Rebranding alignment meetings removes the sales team's guard. If your ABM program feels like a reporting exercise for sales, rename it. The psychology of naming matters.
                        </AcmeTake>
                    </article>
                </section>


                <!-- ===== SECTION 04: The '18 Pilot ===== -->
                <section class="mb-14" id="pilot">
                    <SectionHeader number="04" title="The '18 ABSM Pilot" />

                    <article class="article-prose space-y-6">
                        <p>
                            The ABSM program set clear goals for its first rollout: grow business in mid-market and named accounts, establish and measure an effective ABM approach, maximize contribution to sales pipeline, and get a quick win.
                        </p>

                        <ArticleFigure
                            src="https://placehold.co/900x500/faf9f6/1a1a1a?text=Autodesk+MarTech+Stack+%E2%80%94+CRM+%2B+Automation+%2B+Orchestration"
                            alt="Autodesk MarTech Stack"
                            caption="The pilot marketing technology stack at Autodesk: CRM, marketing automation, account data & insights, personalized interactions, orchestration, and measurement tools."
                            icon="ph-bold ph-stack"
                        />

                        <DataTable
                            headers={["Pilot Element", "Detail"]}
                            rows={[
                                ["Total Accounts", "7,705 accounts across US, Europe, Middle East, and Asia Pacific"],
                                ["Team Size", "3 global teams, 49 ABM managers and marketers"],
                                ["Verticals", "AEC (Architecture, Engineering, Construction), D&M (Design & Manufacturing), M&E (Media & Entertainment)"],
                                ["Focus", "Named accounts + mid-market + ENR400 companies"]
                            ]}
                        />
                    </article>
                </section>


                <!-- ===== SECTION 05: What Really Worked ===== -->
                <section class="mb-14" id="what-worked">
                    <SectionHeader number="05" title="What Really Worked" />

                    <article class="article-prose space-y-6">

                        <h3 class="text-xl brand-font uppercase text-[#006AB4]">Going Beyond "Hi &lt;First_Name&gt;"</h3>

                        <p>
                            Autodesk recognized early the power of personalization in their one-to-few and one-to-many approaches. Using <strong>Folloze</strong>, they built microsites and content hubs tailored to each account, scaling the ABM program to 10,000 global accounts within a year.
                        </p>

                        <ArticleFigure
                            src="https://placehold.co/900x450/006AB4/ffffff?text=Example+ABM+Microsite+Built+Using+Folloze"
                            alt="ABM microsite example"
                            caption="An example of an ABM microsite built using Folloze. Co-branded, with dedicated points of contact and tailored content for each account."
                            icon="ph-bold ph-browser"
                        />

                        <h3 class="text-xl brand-font uppercase text-[#E31C25]">Digital + Physical = Experiences Remarkable</h3>

                        <p>
                            Autodesk created a campaign targeting six stakeholders from the buying committee: three received miniature vaults, three received codes to open them. Once they found each other, they unlocked access to a personalised microsite. The messaging? "Chasing people around for the latest design copy takes time. Here is the better way to do it!"
                        </p>

                        <ArticleFigure
                            src="https://placehold.co/900x400/FFC906/1a1a1a?text=Direct+Mail+Campaign+%E2%80%94+Vault+%2B+Code+%2B+Microsite"
                            alt="Direct mail campaign driving to Folloze board"
                            caption="Scalable personalization: direct mail campaign with miniature vaults driving to personalized Folloze boards."
                            icon="ph-bold ph-package"
                        />

                        <h3 class="text-xl brand-font uppercase text-black">Curated Content for Executive Eyes</h3>

                        <p>
                            The award-winning ABM content team created their own publishing platform, <strong>'Converge'</strong> (later rebranded as 'Design & Make'), to publish executive-level content. The strategy was three-pronged: always-on, executive-level, and regionally tailored.
                        </p>

                        <SpeakerQuote
                            quote="If you carry on using the same 'inside-out' content that you've been using for lead generation, then chances are your ABM program will not see the results you're looking for."
                            speakerName="Stephanie Losee"
                            speakerTitle="Dir. Executive & ABM Content, Autodesk"
                            initials="SL"
                            color="blue"
                        />

                        <!-- Content Campaign Results Table -->
                        <DataTable
                            headers={["Metric", "Result"]}
                            rows={[
                                ["Executives Engaged", "1,570"],
                                ["Opt-Ins for Future Content", "171"],
                                ["Report Downloads vs Target", "Exceeded by 62%"],
                                ["Workshop Attendees vs Target", "Exceeded by 20%"],
                                ["Took Inspiration for Business", "56% of workshop attendees"]
                            ]}
                        />

                        <AcmeTake color="blue">
                            Building your own content platform (like Converge) is a power move. It positions you as a publisher, not a vendor. If you're running executive ABM, your content can't live on a gated landing page. Give it a home that feels editorial.
                        </AcmeTake>
                    </article>
                </section>


                <!-- ===== SECTION 06: Outcomes ===== -->
                <section class="mb-14" id="outcomes">
                    <SectionHeader number="06" title="Outcomes & What's Next" />

                    <article class="article-prose space-y-6">
                        <p>
                            Autodesk's revenue grew from <strong>$2.1 billion in FY18 to $5.34 billion in FY24</strong>, an increase of 150 percent. EBITDA went from a negative $401 million to a positive $1.46 billion. Market cap doubled in just four years, recovering to $48 billion by end of Q2 FY23.
                        </p>

                        <ArticleFigure
                            src="https://placehold.co/900x450/1a1a1a/E31C25?text=Autodesk+Revenue+%242.1B+%E2%86%92+%245.3B+%28FY18%E2%80%93FY24%29"
                            alt="Autodesk revenue growth chart"
                            caption="Revenue history for Autodesk from FY18 to FY24: 150% growth driven by subscription transition and account-based GTM."
                            icon="ph-bold ph-chart-line-up"
                        />

                        <h3 class="text-xl brand-font uppercase text-[#006AB4]">What's Next</h3>

                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>AI Integration:</strong> Internally developing Autodesk GPT for consistency, relevancy and accuracy in customer data output.</li>
                            <li><strong>AI-powered Customer Queries:</strong> Implementing AI systems to handle common queries, freeing sales for complex interactions.</li>
                            <li><strong>Scalability:</strong> Balancing one-to-one, one-to-few, and one-to-many ABM approaches for personalized experiences at scale.</li>
                            <li><strong>Process Standardization:</strong> Defining processes for greater sales alignment and deploying across the organization.</li>
                        </ul>

                        <AcmeTake color="black">
                            Autodesk's journey proves that ABM isn't a campaign &mdash; it's an operating model. The companies that treat ABM as a program with an end date will plateau. The ones that embed it into how sales and marketing operate together will compound.
                        </AcmeTake>
                    </article>
                </section>


                <!-- ===== KEY QUOTES ===== -->
                <section class="mb-14" id="quotes">
                    <SectionHeader number="07" title="Key Quotes" />
                    <div class="space-y-4">
                        <div class="bg-[#1a1a1a] text-white p-5 border-4 border-black">
                            <p class="slab-text italic text-base leading-relaxed mb-3">
                                "He made this announcement not only internally at Autodesk, but also to our shareholders, on our financial earnings call, to Wall Street and to our board of directors. We had a lot of eyes on our program, and the pressure was on."
                            </p>
                            <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
                                <div class="w-6 h-6 bg-[#FFC906] text-black flex items-center justify-center font-black text-[8px] flex-shrink-0">NM</div>
                                <p class="text-xs font-bold text-gray-400 uppercase">Nathalie N. Moore &mdash; AEC ABM Manager, Autodesk</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
